y and global context indicative of the changing patterns of city life.While the topic of cultural change is not necessarily new to African art history and cultural studies, few scholars or writers have attempted to understand why African arts so readily change. This book, the first full-length monograph addressing contemporary art in Calabar, explains the fluidity and thriving nature of masquerade by analyzing the ways in which masking is steeped in economic transaction and how street performances have become more public and spatially calculated. By unraveling the urban layers of masquerade arts and their performances, this book shows how so-called traditional culture gains new roles or currencies within a contemporary, city-based context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMasqueradesxEconomic aspectszNigeriazCalabar. 0aMasqueradeszNigeriazCalabar. 0aPerforming artsxSocial aspectszNigeriazCalabar. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aArt & Architecture. 4aLegend Myth & Folklore. 7aHISTORY / Africa / West.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aAfrican Art.  aArt history.  aCalabar.  aCross River Region.  aCulture.  aEconomics of Art.  aEconomics.  aEkpe.  aMasquerade.  aMgbe.  aNigeria.  aPerformance.  aRitual.  aSecret Societies.  aSlave Trade.  aTraditional Art.  aUrban.  aWest Africa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311143099740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800104211?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800104211423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800104211/original  a978-3-11-143099-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles